qx|A3|pn|hondo717,BabsG (Babs),foxyausy (Gail),fairwell (Irene)|st||sk|s|md|1S59QKH458D58QC39K,S78H26JAD239JKAC5,STJAH9TD7C468TJQA,|rh||ah|Board 3|ah|hondo717 mentoring session|ah|November 13, 2013|sv|e|mb|p|mb|1D|mb|2C|mb|p|lb|*bWhat should be the bid by South? Please note that there might be more than one correct answers -:).^^3c|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me discuss a couple of points on bidding after partner overcalls. First, you need to decide if a new suit by responder (me) is forcing or not. I absolutely think it should be, but some people play it is not forcing. |
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you play a new suit as forcing, then I can cue bid, one of my choices, to show a limit raise in clubs which is what I like to play. And that one reason (among several) is why I think a new suit should be forcing. But if you don't play a new suit is forcing then a cue bid is simply a nondescript forcing bid.|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Assuming you play my recommendation of a cue bid as a limit raise you then have to decide how many trump it shows. Most people play a cue bid only guarantees 3-card support. But I like to play it tends to show 4-card support. A 9-card fit is much better than an 8-card fit. So I will bid a new suit often when I have 3-card support, if feasible. |
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On this hand I do have 10 points and 3-card support. But even if you play 2@D shows a limit raise but only guarantees 3-card support I would not bid 2@D with this hand for the following reasons:|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT|^B@2
a) I only have 3 card support
b) my @DQ is suspect
c) my distribution is very flat
d) 3@C is more preemptive. so I bid 3@C.|MB|3c|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


AT| 3@C shows less than a limit raise, 6-9 or so.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On the other hand, some people play that there is a way to differentiate between 3 card and 4 card limit raise. Both a cue bid and 2N show limit raises of differing length. Again, some people play the cheaper bid (2@D in this case) shows 3 card support, and the higher bid (2N in this case) shows 4 card support.|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Others play that the cue bid always shows 3 card support and 2N shows 4 card support (or vice versa). The point is there is a way, if you play that, to differentiate between 3 and 4 card limit raises which is particularly important when your suit is a major. Because you want to stretch to bid game with a 9-card fit (eg. pard has 4-card support) and be more conservative with 3-card support.|
