up|41|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|We already discussed the bidding point on this board. Now, let me explain why Babs, at trick 2, should figure out the best defense. It is a matter of counting, which it often is on defense. Put aside for the moment that partner supported Babs (although that is definitely something Babs should take into account). |
PG| ***** 77 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Irene lead a low diamond, which means she has 1 or 3. If she has 3 (likely on the bidding) that means Gail only has 1, since Babs sees 9 diamonds between her hand and dummy. Babs needs to figure out where they are going to get their tricks. They already have 1 diamond, but they need 2 more tricks. |
PG| ***** 78 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If partner has the @SA then its easy, they get 3 aces. But if partner does not have the @SA it is very possible that the spade suit will provide some discards. Then assuming no club tricks, and knowing that North has no more diamonds Babs has to lead the @HA to make sure they get 2 heart tricks if they are entitled to them. This is why defense is so hard.|
PG| ***** 79 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And finally let us address the 4@D bid by East. Bidding 4@D can be dangerous. However, Irene correctly surmised that if Babs can bid 3@D all by herself, 4@D is reasonable with 3 card support. |
PG| ***** 80 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, (and this is especially true when the opps suit is a major) bidding 4 of a minor can push the opponents into a makeable game. So although 4@D is not dangerous it may push them into a makeable game. But as it turns out, with best defense 5@C is down 1, so 4@D should have worked out well.|
PG| ***** 81 ***** |


