NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Some people play a convention called Smolen, which is ok, but I don't particularly recommend it. If you play Smolen, rather than bidding 3@S I would bid 3@H. So playing Smolen the auction 1N-2@C-2@D-3@H shows 5 SPADES (not hearts) and 4 hearts. The reason for playing that is so that the strong hand ends up as declarer always.|
PG| ***** 117 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Over 3@H the NT bidder would bid 4@S with 3 spades and otherwise 3N. There is often a slight advantage to having the strong hand hidden and the weaker hand as dummy. But the reason I don't particularly recommend Smolen is that this sequence rarely comes up, and partners often forget they are playing Smolen and might think mistakenly that the 3@H bid shows 5 hearts and 4 spades. Just to avoid bidding problems, I think playing the jump to 3@S as natural is a better way to go. Of course on this hand it is all irrelevant.|
