^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This is a complicated hand to play but the contract can be made. Let me discuss how an expert might play it. There are 4 potential losers. 1 spade, 1 heart, and 2 clubs. But there are chances to eliminate some of them. |
pg| ***** 134 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's start with the spades. I know there is the famous (but often incorrect) bridge saying "8 ever, 9 never" meaning you should not finesse for the queen with a 9 card fit. But that is not really true. First of all without any information from the bidding or the play, the odds of the Queen dropping are only about 52%. |
PG| ***** 135 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But you often have information from the bidding, as on this hand. And even if you don't, the finesse and the drop are essentially equal plays. However, you can greatly increase your odds if one opponent has shown a long suit. |
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As in this case where Babs showed long diamonds. Then, you should assume the person with the long suit is more likely to be short in trump and finesse the other person for the Queen. So more often than not, you end up finessing rather than playing for the drop.|
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If Irene does that she makes. But she has other chances as well. The heart finesse is irrelevant, because even if it wins, she still has a heart loser. However, she can try clubs first, which gives her 2 chances. |
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First, if Babs has the @CQ she will only lose 1 club trick. 2nd, even if Gail has the @CQ, she can set up 2 club tricks in her hand, and pitch one of dummy's hearts on the @DA and the other on the long club. So it turns out an expert would make 5 on this hand, losing 2 clubs and nothing else.|
PG| ***** 139 ***** |


