qx|X1|pn|hondo717,Bernie000,coupkoo,kadu|st||sk|n|md|2S58H256AD47QACJKA,,S67QKAH79QKD68KC7,|rh||ah|Board 1A|ah|hondo717 mentoring session|ah|November 14, 2014|sv|b|AT|
^B@2^*BMM: ^*NNorth/South play 2/1.|
PG| ***** 144 ***** |


mb|p|lb|*bWhat should North bid?^^1s|mb|1S|mb|p|sk|s|NT||lb|*bPlaying 2/1 what should South bid?^^2d|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|With 18 HCP mostly in prime cards I know that we should be at least in game. 2@D bid is a game force. I cannot bid 2@H because I need 5 hearts for that bid.|mb|2D|
PG| ***** 147 ***** |


mb|p|sk|n|NT||lb|*bWhat should be the bid?^^2h|mb|2H|mb|p|sk|s|lb|*bWhat should be the bid?^^3h|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Playing 2/1, 3@H is stronger than 4@H and is a slam try. The principle of "fast arrival" applies to all 2/1 auctions. The quicker you bid game, the weaker your hand is. So a 4@H bid by me would be weaker than 3@H. My 2@D established a game force so I know partner cannot pass 3@H. By bidding 4@H, I am taking away a lot of room for exploring for slam. So I should only bid 4@H if I have no slam interest. My 3@H bid asks partner to bid controls if she has any interest in slam.|mb|3H|
pg| ***** 150 ***** |


mb|p|sk|n|NT||lb|*bWhat should be the bid?^^3s|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|We have established hearts as trump so 3S is not an attempt to play in spades. It is a "control bid" showing at least some slam interest and first or second round control in spades (A, K, singleton, or void). On this hand 3@S must show the A or K since the 1@S opener guaranteed partner does not have a singleton or void. You bid controls up the line. So if, on a different hand, partner bid 4@C over 3@H, that would show a club control and also deny a spade control (since partner skipped bidding 3@S).|mb|3S|
pg| ***** 152 ***** |


mb|p|sk|s|NT||lb|*bWhat should South bid?^^4n|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|We have all suits controlled and all I need to know is how many keycards we have. So I bid 4N.|mb|4N|
pg| ***** 154 ***** |


mb|p|sk|n|NT||lb|*bPlaying either 0314 or 1430 what should be the bid?^^5s|mb|5S|an|2 keycards /with trump queen|
pg| ***** 156 ***** |


mb|p|NT||sk|s|lb|*bWhat should be the bid now?^^6h|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I know we have all the key cards and the trump Q. So I could ask for kings (bid 5N) and if partner has 2 (which would have to be the @SK and the @DK) we could easily be making 7.|
PG| ***** 158 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There are 2 methods for responding to 5N. One method is "specific kings". Partner bids the lowest outside king she has over 5N. So, playing that method, on this hand, partner would bid 6@D. This denies the @CK and shows the @DK. (It says nothing about the @SK). |
PG| ***** 159 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The other method is ## of kings. Since 4N already asked about the trump king, 5N asks about the ## of kings not counting the trump King. Even if you play 1430 over 4N, over 5N you play straight Blackwood responses. So over 5N, 6@C shows 0 kings, 6@D shows 1 king, 6@H shows 2 kings, and 6@S shows 3 kings.|
PG| ***** 160 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Many experts like to play specific kings because sometimes knowing that partner has a particular king is more important than how many kings. For example, if I had a singleton spade, I would only care about the @DK. |
PG| ***** 161 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, I prefer ## of kings for 2 reasons. First, often ## of kings is more useful. For example, on this hand, it is much more useful for me to know that North has 2 kings, because I then know I have no diamond nor spade losers. If I were playing specific kings, North would respond 6@D and I would have no idea whether or not North also had the @SK. |
PG| ***** 162 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Second, if the lowest specific king is in a suit higher than the trump suit, you have to decide whether or not partner should show it. For example, on this hand, suppose North had only the @SK but not the @DK. If South is allowed to bid 6@S (bypassing 6@H) then I know we have a potential diamond loser but we are already passed by 6@H. |
PG| ***** 163 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So some people play you can only show specific kings when spades are trumps. Others play you can also bid specific kings when hearts are trump (but not when diamonds or clubs are trump) but you are not allowed to bid 6@S. The whole specific king approach seems unnecessarily complicated to me, and it is not always as useful as ## of kings. So that is why I play ## of kings.|
PG| ***** 164 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now back to whether or not I should bid 5N, and if partner shows 2 kings (by responding 6@H), whether or not I should bid 7. I know we have no losers in any suit. So 7 only depends on a 3-2 break. However, as I explained in my recent lesson on scoring, in theory you should only bid 7 if you can just about count 13 tricks. |
PG| ***** 165 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The odds should exceed 80% that 7 makes. Since a 4-1 break happens almost 1/3 of the time, a grand slam that depends on a 3-2 break should theoretically not be bid. That is why at the teaching table I only bid 6. But at a real table, I might very well bid 7 despite the mathematics, because bidding and making 7 is always very exciting.|
PG| ***** 166 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to whether you should play in NT or a suit, in general it is much easier to play slam in a suit rather than in NT. In fact, there are some hands where, even when you have a 7-card fit, slam makes in a suit contract and 6NT does not make. That is because you can sometimes score extra tricks by ruffing in the short hand. |
PG| ***** 167 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So in IMPs you should always prefer playing in 6 of a suit to playing 6NT. However, in Match Points, 6NT is worth 10 extra points over 6 of a major and 70 extra points over 6 of a minor. So if you are pretty sure you have 12 tricks in NT, it is ok to bid 6N rather than 6 of a suit. |
PG| ***** 168 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Playing Match Points, if I chose to bid 6 rather than 7, I would bid 6N rather than 6@H. But if I bid 7, I would bid 7@H, not 7NT because on many hands, the extra ruff could easily be my 13th trick.|mb|6H|
pg| ***** 169 ***** |


