sk|s|NT||lb|*bPlease help South to make a bid^^5d|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is possible that clubs is a better contract than diamonds. It is also possible that 5 of a minor will go down. But there is no way to figure that out for certain. Also, with a heart void, I know the opponents almost always have at least a 9-card fit (the NT bidder will almost never have a 5-card suit and often not even a 4-card suit). |
PG| ***** 187 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So they will be interfering in the auction if I go slow. When you have a choice of 2 suits and have no way of having partner help you decide, as on this hand, you should favor length over strength. It is much more likely we have at least a 9-card fit in diamonds (since partner only needs 3-card support) than in clubs (partner needs 4-card support). |
PG| ***** 188 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And a 9-card fit is much better than an 8-card fit. So, on this hand, I bid what I think will most likely get us a good result, which is 5@D. I have 5 potential losers (3 diamonds, 1 club, 1 spade) and hopefully partner can cover at least 3 of them.|mb|5D|
pg| ***** 189 ***** |


sk|w|NT||lb|*bWhat could be the bid?^^5h|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|5@H is a great bid for a number of reasons. On these hands, you need to "picture" likely holdings for partner to help you figure out what to do. The diamond void is huge, and West can assume at least a 10-card fit, since East's 2@H bid normally promises a 6-card suit over 1NT. |
PG| ***** 191 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If East has as little as a doubleton club and AKxxxx of hearts, 5@H makes. It will be very surprising if 5@H goes down more than 1. The only other consideration for West is a tactical one. If she bids 5@H, will she push them into a makable slam that they otherwise would not bid? With the @SAK, she should welcome their bidding 6 because it is quite possible that she can cash 2 spade tricks (and she will be on lead). So that is another reason why 5@H is a great bid.|mb|5H|
pg| ***** 192 ***** |


sk|n|NT||lb|*bWhat should be the bid by North?^^6d|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|6@D is another great bid. North has a tougher problem over 5@H. She has some great cards, the @DAK and the @CA. The @HA might be useful as well, although it is virtually certain that South is short in hearts (based on the 5@D bid) and could even have a void. The main question is whether or not there are 2 immediate spade losers. |
PG| ***** 194 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And even if there are, a heart lead is somewhat likely and the @HA might provide a discard of a losing spade if South is void in hearts. Also, with 4-card diamond support, it is quite possible there is a void in diamonds, so N/S may get no diamond tricks. Therefore, 6@D is a good bid.|
PG| ***** 195 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| It might go down, but it has a lot of upside. As it turns out, 6@D makes. So the "par" contract is 6@H doubled down 2. The "par" contract is the contract that gives the best result for all sides given the lie of the cards. On this hand, since 6@D makes and 7@D does not, 6@H doubled is "par".|mb|6D|
