qx|X3|pn|hondo717,Bernie000,kadu,coupkoo|st||sk|E|md|4S2489TH67D236C48Q,S3567JKHTD8QC69JA,SQAH489D47TJKAC57,|rh||ah|Board 3A|ah|hondo717 mentoring session|ah|November 14, 2014|sv|e|lb|*bMake a reasonable bid for East^^4h|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is reasonable to open either 1@H or 4@H with that hand. It is a matter of tactics and risk/reward. The advantage of opening 4@H is tactical. 4@H is by far the most likely contract you want to be in, and so if you bid it right away you make it more difficult for the opponents to compete accurately. |
PG| ***** 207 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The downside of 4@H is that there is a small danger that you will miss a slam. As with many hands, a good technique is to "picture" reasonable hands for partner. On this deal, partner could have as little as the @DA and a doubleton @CA with a couple of hearts and 6 would be a reasonable contract. There are many other hands partner could hold as well. |
PG| ***** 208 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, it is much more likely that partner will not hold a hand where 6@H makes, so I prefer opening 4@H to 1@H. Note that the hand is not good enough to open 2@C as it neither meets the Howard 9 trick rule nor the Bergen 4 and 4 rule.|mb|4H|
pg| ***** 209 ***** |


mb|p|mb|p|sk|n|NT||lb|*bWhat should be the bid?^^p|mb|5d|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|5@D is not unreasonable, especially given the vulnerability. When deciding whether to bid over an opponent's game bid, you need to look at several factors. One is the length and strength of your suit. With the North hand, that factor is definitely in favor of bidding, with a 6 card diamond suit with 4 honors. |
PG| ***** 211 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Another factor is vulnerability. Again, on this hand, that factor favors bidding because you are not vulnerable and the opponents are vulnerable.  A third factor is your overall distribution. You prefer to bid with shapely hands, hands with a singleton or void. That factor is not in North's favor. 6-3-2-2 is the flattest you can be with a 6-card suit. |
PG| ***** 212 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|A fourth factor is length in the opponents suit. A void is magic, and a singleton is good. Again, that factor favors not bidding with the North hand. Partner is likely to be short in hearts and passed. So although partner could have a moderate hand, he or she cannot have a good hand.|
PG| ***** 213 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also, there is some possibility that you will set 4@H. You probably have at least 1 diamond trick (voids are rare) and you might get lucky and get 2 diamond tricks. You have at least 1 spade trick and could very easily have 2 spade tricks. |
PG| ***** 214 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On the auction, even if partner does not have the @SK, it is more likely to be with West than East. And partner more than likely has a trick (if not, then 5@D is destined to go down too many). So I would say it is far from clear whether or not North should bid 5@D. And that is why 4@H is such a good opening bid.|
