^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me briefly explain about the 1@S bid and how to respond after your RHO has doubled. I play if you don't redouble (or bid 2N which I will explain in a minute) you have less than 10 points. With 10 or more points you must redouble. Failing to redouble denies 10 points. However, most experts play something more complicated which I find very counter intuitive. |
PG| ***** 237 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And that is if they bid on the 1-level over a double that is forcing. It doesn't promise 10 points, but they can bid at the 1 level with 10 points. So 1@D-X-1@S is forcing, and doesn't say anything about how strong you are (other than you have 6+). And they play that 2 level bids are weak and non-forcing. |
PG| ***** 238 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Therefore, 1@D-X-2@C is weak, whereas 1@D-X-1@S can be strong I find that very counter intuitive. I try to keep it simple. if my partner does not redouble, they don"t have 10 points. The only other way to show a strong hand is to bid 2N over the double. That is known as Jordan 2N and shows a 4+ card limit raise. So the auction 1x-dbl-2N shows a limit raise after a double.|
PG| ***** 239 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| Thus, IMO, 1@S by Gail denies 10 points. 1@S is an ok bid but I can give you an undo if you wish.|
